      <hedline>
        <hl1>How to Quench a Thirst for Oil</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Scott McMurren letter says US energy policy must highlight development of domestic oil and gas reserves, including those in Arctic National Wildlife Refuge</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Politics of Fuel'' (editorial, Oct. 2):</p>
        <p>As a nation, we must hedge our energy habit with domestic resources. Your suggestion that American companies consider tapping offshore supplies in Russia and Africa is off the mark. There are no human rights considerations or environmental safeguards in either place.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''The Politics of Fuel'' (editorial, Oct. 2):</p>
        <p>As a nation, we must hedge our energy habit with domestic resources. Your suggestion that American companies consider tapping offshore supplies in Russia and Africa is off the mark. There are no human rights considerations or environmental safeguards in either place.</p>
        <p>Ten years ago, we went to war in the Persian Gulf over oil. Today, America's oil and gas industry operates under the most stringent environmental regulations in the world. Tomorrow, a national energy policy must hedge against the money that OPEC extorts from us every day.</p>
        <p>In addition to conservation and alternative-energy sources like gas and clean-burning coal, our policy must highlight development of our domestic oil and gas reserves, including resources within the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge.</p>
        <p>SCOTT MCMURREN  Anchorage, Oct. 2, 2000</p>
      </block>
